diff:1262673275:1262494839:=5d4%0a%3c !!! Release of simuPOP 1.0.0 (Draft, Jan. 6th, 2010)%0a8,30c7,10%0a%3c After more than a year's hard work, I am happy to announce the release of simuPOP 1.0.0. This release marks the end of the tumultuous 0.9.x series and the beginning of the new 1.x.x development cycle when backward compatibility will be enforced. All simuPOP users should upgrade to this release.%0a%3c %0a%3c Due to substantial changes to the simuPOP core and interface, this release is incompatible with previous versions of simuPOP. If you have been following the development of the 0.9.x series, this release introduces the following changes to the 0.9.9 release:%0a%3c %0a%3c 1. In order to make simuPOP conform better to Python style guide and avoid potential confusion and misuse of simuPOP, I have renamed all global functions from CapWords to mixedCases, and class names from mixedCases to CapWords. This has been a very difficult decision to make because it essentially changes all names of simuPOP.%0a%3c %0a%3c 2. Parameter matingScheme has been moved from the Simulator() function to the Simulator.evolve() function, replacing the position of parameter duringOps. This change simplifies the use of during-mating operators because these operators now can only be used in the ops parameter of mating schemes.%0a%3c %0a%3c 3. A new function Population.evolve() has been introduced to evolve a population directly. The role of simulators is therefore less important than before because you only need to use a simulator if you would like to simulate multiple populations simultaneously. %0a%3c %0a%3c 4. As I have described in an earlier email to the mailing list, simuPOP now inquires parameter names of user-defined functions in order to determine what information should be passed these functions. This simplifies the use of user-defined functions because parameters such as pyOperator(offspringOnly) are no longer needed. A utility class WithArgs was introduced to allow the use of arbitrary argument lists in user-defined functions. %0a%3c %0a%3c The differences between simuPOP 1.0.0 and the last stable release 0.8.8 are too numerous to list here. Although upgrading from the 0.8.8 release implies major changes to your scripts, users of the 0.8.8 release should here are some reasons why you should upgrade:%0a%3c %0a%3c 1. simuPOP 1.0 has complete support for virtual subpopulations (VSP). All classes and functions are now should %0a%3c %0a%3c You may still remember an email I sent early last year, asking support for my application for external funding to support the development of simuPOP. I sincerely appreciate your help in writing letters of supports. Unfortunately, my grant application has been denied. Although I will continue to develop the core of simuPOP, many of my more ambitious development plans such as a graphical evolutionary process constructor has to be delayed, due to lack of manpower. I will continue to seek for external support and may ask your help again. In the meantime, please remember to cite simuPOP if you have used simuPOP for any of your publications. These citations will help me.%0a%3c %0a%3c Enjoy!%0a%3c Bo%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a---%0a> After more than a year's hard work, I am happy to announce the release of simuPOP 1.0.0. This release marks the end of the tumultuous 0.9.x series because backward compatibility will be ensured starting from this release.%0a> %0a> This release is incompatible with previous simuPOP releases, to a level that very few of the previous simuPOP scripts will work without modification. Compare to the previous stable release, %0a> %0a
