diff:1254009986:1254006573:=7,70c7,16%0a%3c simuPOP takes another stride towards its 1.0 release when backward%0a%3c compatibility will be enforced. Before that, you are seeing another%0a%3c incompatible release that will likely break your existing script.%0a%3c Please be patient with me: all the changes are for the better and your%0a%3c suffer is expected to be over in a few months. Although new users are%0a%3c encouraged to use the latest release, existing users are not%0a%3c recommended to upgrade unless you need to use some of the new features%0a%3c described below. Note that the online documentation always reflects%0a%3c the latest release.%0a%3c %0a%3c The first major change is the reorganization of utility modules.%0a%3c Instead of several separated modules, simuPOP is now organized as a%0a%3c package. Module @@simuUtil@@ is now @@simuPOP.utils@@, and @@simuRPy@@ is now%0a%3c @@simuPOP.plotter@@. The @@simuOpt@@ module is kept out of simuPOP but the%0a%3c @@simuOpt.simuOpt@@ class has been renamed to @@simuOpt.simuParam@@ due to%0a%3c potential name conflicts. A completely rewritten set of classes and%0a%3c functions that simulate trajectories of allele frequencies have been%0a%3c added to @@simuPOP.utils@@. The new functions are more flexible and can%0a%3c handle complicated demographic and genetic features such as population%0a%3c split and merge, varying and population-specific selection pressures,%0a%3c and gene gene interaction.%0a%3c %0a%3c Another big change that will affect many existing scripts is the%0a%3c separation of @@initSex@@ from operators @@initByFreq@@ and @@initByValue@@. For%0a%3c the sake of convenience, @@initByFreq@@ and @@initByValue@@ have always calls @@initSex@@ by%0a%3c default. This has lead to some errors when multiple initialization%0a%3c operators are used and some of them are sex-dependent. With the%0a%3c introduction of a new operator @@initInfo@@ that initializes individual%0a%3c information fields, @@initSex@@ has been separated from these two%0a%3c operators. Consequently, @@initSex@@ now needs to be explicitly used%0a%3c whenever @@randomMating@@ is used.%0a%3c %0a%3c At a more advanced level, the way how during-mating operators are%0a%3c handled has been changed slightly. The concept of '''genotype%0a%3c transmitter''' and related special handling of these operators have been%0a%3c removed. Consequently, all during-mating operators are handled%0a%3c according to a simpler set of rules. The most visible change is that%0a%3c @@recombinator@@ should now be used in the @@ops@@ parameter of a mating%0a%3c scheme to replace the default genotype transmitter. The existing usage%0a%3c (use it in @@simulator.evolve@@) is allowed, but will lead to reduced%0a%3c performance.%0a%3c %0a%3c The tagging operators have been revisited in this release. New%0a%3c operators @@idTagger@@, @@summaryTagger@@ and @@pedigreeTagger@@ have been%0a%3c introduced, and the existing operators such as @@inheritTagger@@ have been%0a%3c enhanced. The introduction of @@idTagger@@ allows you to give every%0a%3c individual in an evolving population an unique ID so that you can%0a%3c easily identify ancestors. A function @@population.indByID@@ has been%0a%3c added to look up an individual by its ID from a multi-generational%0a%3c population. This feature is currently used to dump all recombination%0a%3c events, but will be used in all pedigree-related features (e.g.%0a%3c pedigree ascertainment) later on. Please check the use's guide for%0a%3c details.%0a%3c %0a%3c Finally, simuPOP now accepts locus-specific allele names. That is to%0a%3c say, the same numeric alleles can corresponds to different alleles at%0a%3c different loci. This feature is introduced so that simuPOP can better%0a%3c handle the HapMap and other genetic datasets that uses the same 0 and%0a%3c 1 coding for different nucleotides at different loci. Adding%0a%3c locus-specific allele names make it easy, for example, to selected a%0a%3c subset of loci from these datasets with losing their allele%0a%3c information.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a---%0a> Due to the incompatible way simuPOP is currently progressing, your existing script might not run due to the following changes:%0a> * @@initSex()@@ is now separated from @@initByFreq@@ and @@initByValue@@. That is to say, an explicit @@initSex()@@ is always needed to use @@randomMating@@.%0a> * Module @@simuUtil@@ is now a submodule @@simuPOP.utils@@.%0a> * Module @@simuRPy@@ is now a submodule @@simuPOP.plotter@@.%0a> * class @@simuOpt.simuOpt@@ is renamed to @@simuOpt.simuParam@@ due to potential name conflict.%0a> * Parameter ops of a mating scheme now must accept a full list of during-mating operators because this parameter now replaces, instead of appends to, the default genotype transmitter.%0a> %0a> Most new features are around taggers. There are two new tagging operators @@idTagger@@ and @@summaryTagger@@, and the existing taggers have been revised. The introduction of @@idTagger@@ allows you to give every individual in an evolving population an unique ID so that you can easily identify ancestors. This feature is currently used to dump all recombination events, but will be used in all pedigree-related features (e.g. pedigree ascertainment) later on. Please check the use's guide for details. Additional features include an operator @@initInfo@@, and a function @@population.indByID@@ to locate an individual from its ID. Finally, this version of simuPOP introduces locus-specific allele names which makes it easier to work with datasets (such as the HapMap dataset) that use the same 0, 1 coding for different alleles.%0a> %0a> %0a
